of the rivers;'' the reference is to the Hydaspes and Orontes, over which Bacchus is said to have walked dryshod; and “flecto’' here must be taken either in the sense of “to bow ’' or “direct,’' or, in its more metaphorical sense, “to appease.‘' By “mare barbarum” is meant the Indian Ocean.

‡ Orelli observes that in this stanza there are two images‚——one at the entrance of Liber into Hades‚ when Cerberus gently wags his tail to greet him—the other when Liber is leaving and the Hell-dog licks his feet. The poet thus expresses the security with which the god passes through the terrors of the nether world.
